                  "body": {
                    "type": "TextualBody",
                    "value": "<p>“promotion of devotion, order, and decorum” while<lb/> indeed the standard is of the\n                people's own making<lb/> and has no connection whatever with the reli<lb/>gion of\n                the Bible, it was necessary to controvert<lb/> the same three articles on the\n                subject having<lb/> been sent to the Chronicle as you have doubt<lb/>less seen in a\n                late number. When changes are<lb/> known to be proposed in the spirit of religion,\n                I<lb/> have no doubt the present opponents would<lb/> be among the first to hail all\n                improvements.<lb/> But I allude to these things confidentially.<lb/> It is generally\n                my opinion that the least<lb/> said about them the better, if it can be helped,<lb/>\n                for man's disposition seems often to have an<lb/> infatuation in favor of\n                contradiction, and<lb/> the more opposition his inclinations meet with<lb/> the more\n                strengthened they become whether for<lb/> good or for evil. At the present time, we\n                are,<lb/> thank God, in the enjoyment of the great bles<lb/>sing of peace, and I\n                sincerely hope that it may<lb/> long continue, and be a progressive one. About<lb/>\n                <persName>Mr. S.</persName> I believe among us he has no friend<lb/> who would go to\n                the trouble of speaking to him, which<lb/> would perhaps also be useless. Even when\n                he made</p>"
